    <title>Another triangular number formula</title>
    <content type='html'>&lt;div style="text-align: left;"&gt;The double recurrence relation that defines the higher triangular numbers is a simple one - it is no surprise that they turn up so often.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEjDPSLHyKOjArwcYVQpglA0q-1CXjFJB6Z2PbtwMo_zn6EJaEclg2WrIdUUx286Ba-7G1Lti6eQ_mb0t9hFpCKB6-ZYlegwaaFhpmt_WnmnEoFvZRSfWa_HFty4DynLIDkRspmUEqHlgFY/s1600-h/a1.jpg"&gt;&lt;img src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEjDPSLHyKOjArwcYVQpglA0q-1CXjFJB6Z2PbtwMo_zn6EJaEclg2WrIdUUx286Ba-7G1Lti6eQ_mb0t9hFpCKB6-ZYlegwaaFhpmt_WnmnEoFvZRSfWa_HFty4DynLIDkRspmUEqHlgFY/s400/a1.jpg" border="0" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5298640094403610338" style="display: block; margin-top: 0px; margin-right: auto; margin-bottom: 10px; margin-left: auto; text-align: center; cursor: pointer; width: 168px; height: 132px; " /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;The geometric interpretation is stacking: For a given dimension d, you get the n+1 d-triangular number by stacking the nth d-1 triangular number (the gnomon) onto the nth d-triangular number.  The zero dimensional triangular numbers are just the sequence: 1, 1, 1, 1,..., presumably counting stacks of nothing. The one-dimensional triangular numbers are the naturals: 1, 2, 3, 4, ..., made by stacking the ones of the one-dimensional case. The two dimensional triangular numbers stack the naturals: 1, 3, 6, 10, ..., the three dimensional triangular numbers make pyramids of the triangulars: 1, 4, 10, 20, ....&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEgaPsM_o9Y6C0Ew-EW1f2AHSIxto1OseYMZFCw-Mi0xeN4hzAcyUWKJtiVjiXJfb_jRg8TVzSSR0eAgmFJtvVbeBrhUH7lgjutdazPoHlEvaSl5l_V19coelc5-Z74o02lQA5b2KIQfvVE/s1600-h/pascal.jpg"&gt;&lt;img src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEgaPsM_o9Y6C0Ew-EW1f2AHSIxto1OseYMZFCw-Mi0xeN4hzAcyUWKJtiVjiXJfb_jRg8TVzSSR0eAgmFJtvVbeBrhUH7lgjutdazPoHlEvaSl5l_V19coelc5-Z74o02lQA5b2KIQfvVE/s320/pascal.jpg" border="0" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5298643750951761490" style="display: block; margin-top: 0px; margin-right: auto; margin-bottom: 10px; margin-left: auto; text-align: center; cursor: pointer; width: 320px; height: 290px; " /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;If you write out a difference table for the higher triangular numbers, you end up with Pascal’s triangle. This suggests a nice formula for the triangulars in terms of binomial coefficients:&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEg0JMoh7i74TP-qSt_PIkQwQKbfIxXZ62bWJPrwr2RgeeHyOnomUFLlOlvb1flJjkXZhxmHVxWQPdGuP7XnXyKvS9Dc2PUzsmsLkGL3G-8Kg7aFDgGW4O9JCeQPCk3Is5TaDhtF8lCpJHA/s1600-h/a2.jpg"&gt;&lt;img src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEg0JMoh7i74TP-qSt_PIkQwQKbfIxXZ62bWJPrwr2RgeeHyOnomUFLlOlvb1flJjkXZhxmHVxWQPdGuP7XnXyKvS9Dc2PUzsmsLkGL3G-8Kg7aFDgGW4O9JCeQPCk3Is5TaDhtF8lCpJHA/s400/a2.jpg" border="0" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5298640095021654402" style="display: block; margin-top: 0px; margin-right: auto; margin-bottom: 10px; margin-left: auto; text-align: center; cursor: pointer; width: 180px; height: 124px; " /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;From this, you can obtain another recursive formula that you can use when working with higher triangular numbers (this is the “another” formula for this post):&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEip8rqb1AT4xZ-GOy10WPxP7U8oTWhC0JnDldcJzBZ8OnWw8a6hs0NW2Q-L7__-jKBiDprXWTZtJBdJudHKNXPrszM52ve6pX0T1YYCT9g2jbwIeou33Spu0qXX0Jd05VEKYP8NLL1ghiU/s1600-h/a3.jpg"&gt;&lt;img src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEip8rqb1AT4xZ-GOy10WPxP7U8oTWhC0JnDldcJzBZ8OnWw8a6hs0NW2Q-L7__-jKBiDprXWTZtJBdJudHKNXPrszM52ve6pX0T1YYCT9g2jbwIeou33Spu0qXX0Jd05VEKYP8NLL1ghiU/s400/a3.jpg" border="0" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5298640098396375074" style="display: block; margin-top: 0px; margin-right: auto; margin-bottom: 10px; margin-left: auto; text-align: center; cursor: pointer; width: 190px; height: 124px; " /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;If you vary the defining recurrence relation so that the initial “zero dimensional” value is a number other than 1, you get the other polygonal numbers (square, pentagonal, hexagonal, square-based pyramidal, etc.). In particular, if you let the zero-dimensional value be k-2, you obtain the k-polygonal numbers (k-2 corresponding to the number of triangles in your k-sided polygon).&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;span class="Apple-style-span" style="color: rgb(0, 0, 238); "&gt;&lt;img src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEjZEKonmYbC5FVxHGtBqEV-BdgM9Hof5Zk8C0pQVQNmKrGi3b_vzVmD7vesmEiFOmqMYdnCl4nk0WhJ5g7Yw9ndVwWqIGwhf4lG-5JIkHRdFZ-KF2FJJNoClkGLIabI23qeO9LCUTj20ws/s400/a4.jpg" border="0" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5298640098193934226" style="display: block; margin-top: 0px; margin-right: auto; margin-bottom: 10px; margin-left: auto; text-align: center; cursor: pointer; width: 194px; height: 128px; " /&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;It turns out there is a nice formula for these in terms of binomial coefficients as well: &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEjrzjWf8VzCSU39XsNCcxn2Hawx584mDJVUG1iE0YEQgLS1pnC7_Kw5YeO7IYkKAbE58KiZYHxP9SC-b0uXKC7oVUYgAZLYMWjSXaejt7WJzlxNk5HEI8A56mkFBi3Gs1BIixVb6R0XXl8/s1600-h/a5.jpg"&gt;&lt;img src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEjrzjWf8VzCSU39XsNCcxn2Hawx584mDJVUG1iE0YEQgLS1pnC7_Kw5YeO7IYkKAbE58KiZYHxP9SC-b0uXKC7oVUYgAZLYMWjSXaejt7WJzlxNk5HEI8A56mkFBi3Gs1BIixVb6R0XXl8/s400/a5.jpg" border="0" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5298640099462661106" style="display: block; margin-top: 0px; margin-right: auto; margin-bottom: 10px; margin-left: auto; text-align: center; cursor: pointer; width: 387px; height: 146px; " /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</content>
